statement:
Let

\begin{align*}W = \text{span}\left\{ \left[\begin{array}{c}
1 \\ 2 \\ 3 \\ 4 \end{array}\right], \left[\begin{array}{c}
1 \\ 0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{array}\right], \left[\begin{array}{c}
0 \\ 1 \\ 1 \\ 2 \end{array}\right]
\right\}\end{align*}

Find a basis for the orthogonal complement $W^\bot$ of \emph{W}.

sols:
We first note that there is a relationship between the three vectors,
namely $\left[ \begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 2 & 3 & 4 \\ 
\end{array} \right]  = \left[ \begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 0 & 1 & 0 \\ 
\end{array} \right] + 2 \left[ \begin{array}{cccc}
0 & 1 & 1 & 2 \\ 
\end{array} \right]$. Thus, we get that \emph{W} has dimension 2 and
thus $W^\bot$ is also 2 dimensional. Let V be the matrix of basis
vectors to W,

\begin{align*}V=\begin{bmatrix}
1  &  0\\
0  &  1\\
1  &  1\\
0  &  2\\
\end{bmatrix}.\end{align*}

If $\displaystyle {}x=[a,b,c,d]^T$ is a basis vector to $W^\bot$ then
orthogonality tells us that

\begin{align*}
V^Tx&=0\\
\begin{bmatrix}
1  &  0  &  1  &  0\\
0  &  1  &  1  &  2
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
a\\
b\\
c\\
d
\end{bmatrix}
&=\mathbf{0}\end{align*}

Computing this we get the following relationships

\begin{align*}
a+c&=0\\
b+c+2d&=0\end{align*}

Since the dimension (or rank) of V is two we will have two free
parameters (let's choose \emph{a} and \emph{d}) and so we get that

\begin{align*}
c&=-a\\
b&=-2d-c=-2d+a\end{align*}

and finally that

\begin{align*}x=
\begin{bmatrix}
a\\
-2d+a\\
-a\\
d
\end{bmatrix}
=
a\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
1\\
-1\\
0
\end{bmatrix}
+
d\begin{bmatrix}
0\\
-2\\
0\\
1
\end{bmatrix}\end{align*}

Therefore the two orthogonal vectors
$\left[ \begin{array}{cccc} 1 & 1 & -1 & 0 \\  \end{array} \right] , \left[ \begin{array}{cccc} 0 & -2 & 0 & 1 \\  \end{array} \right]$
are a basis for $W^\bot$. Notice the dimension of $W^\bot$ is the same
as that of \emph{W}.
